The paper deals with the problem of content placement in a high-dimensional regime where demand statistics are unknown and have to be inferred from demands. This involves statistical inference, which is a key aspect of information theory (cs.IT). The problem also involves algorithms for online content placement, which falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the performance of different schemes, which is a common theme in machine learning (cs.LG) and information retrieval (cs.IR). The problem of content placement also has implications for networked systems and distributed computing, which are covered under the sub-categories of social and information networks (cs.SI) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI).
